On my recent visit to India for recreational purposes and of course sight-seeing, I tried some local Indian food from small road side stalls and "Hotels" as the Indian refer to their restaurants and they were so good that it left a kind of taste  that I want to be rekindled in the US. The closest I found is in The Himalayan. Their food taste good and similar to the authentic indian flavors. However,The spice level has been tone down a bit to cater to amercian people but people can ask to modify as they please. I don't always have many days on my hand to visit this place regularly since I work out of state but still I manage to get back here whenever I'm  visiting my mom.

This place not only gives you great food but also a very visually appealing food. I was kinda afraid if I mess up their presentation by digging right into it. One thing that stood out to me that it does not have a diner wibe that I'm used to seeing in most of the American Indian restaurants. I would definitely try other restaurants too, I've got a whole new semester to do some good food hunting.

I had an amazing lunch with my kids there. My kids as being a typical American kids can't handle even moderate spice levels. Therefore, I told them to put no spice at all. They complied and my kids liked the indian food so much that they want to try the original version. :) I like my food to be spicey enough and always ask for extra, that's why mexican and indian is my all time favorite. To pacify the burn I get from spices, which I like, to be honest ,I always go for mango lassi. It's spot on!

I ordered Sunrise Mocktail and was served just orange juice. In the description it had 3 - 4 different types of juices mixed including Grenadine, however I was given just orange juice. When I asked the waitress about this they just took the drink I had and added a splash of Grenadine in the same old drink. Not the best service I experienced compared to my last visit.

One of the worst customer service ever.  In all my 25+ years in the US not once was I asked to move to another table IN THE MIDDLE OF EATING FOOD.  I get that restaurants get busy and need to make last minute accommodations due to crowd or shift tables around but we were asked to move after we had already started eating after appetizers we're served.  And they were pretty insistent that we need to move.  And we moved for fear of them messing up (read that spitting in our food or good alone knows what this restaurant will do in the kitchen if customers don't bow down to their wishes) our rest of the food we ordered.  And we were a party of eight but they were eyeing the dollars and tips for a party of 14.  Why couldn't they have asked the 14 party to wait?  We were on our main course anyway.  And service is horribly horribly slow.  If you want to be respected and want to eat food peacefully, AVOID THIS PLACE.  I wish there is an option for negative review.  And to quality of food - very bland taste and no character and flavor.  Updated review: I just noticed two other poeple's  review where they also commented about being moved to another table after being seated(one day before my review and another a month ago).  Very unprofessional treatment to customers.  As I said, AVOID THIS PLACE AT ALL COSTS.  You are not missing out on any exceptional Indian food by easting in this restaurant.

She gave us 4 menus to share. Drinks and food took a while to come. The drinks and food were good (one star for each).
